from the fifth grade on I went through school at 
Junction riding the bus 15 or so miles each way

00:59.988 --> 01:25.455
every day but I had a good experience with it I 
graduated from there in 1943 immediately tried to

00:59.988 --> 01:25.455
go into the service at that time I was 16 and the 
decided that was a little young. So when I turned

01:28.741 --> 01:40.496
17, in October, that year, I tried again to get into 
the that time I had, I was one of five brothers. The

01:41.357 --> 01:42.999
other four were already in service. And one of them 
was flying B-24s at the time out of Tarrant Field in

01:43.680 --> 01:49.527
Fort Worth. I'd gone up to visit with him. And at 
that time, they were still in the Macho era with the

01:53.735 --> 02:21.733
watch silk scarf around the neck and all that and I 
thought that was the greatest thing I'd ever seen

01:53.735 --> 02:21.733
So I decided I wanted to get in the Air Force I tried 
to enlist in the Air Force and went through all of

01:53.735 --> 02:21.733
the examinations and all and in the federal 
building in San Antonio, they told me that Okay, I

01:53.735 --> 02:21.733
took all the quizzes to come back in two weeks, I 
believe and they let me know how I came out I did I

02:22.102 --> 02:24.985
came back in two weeks, and they said, well, you 
passed everything. Everything is just fine.

02:26.707 --> 02:29.771
Said, you will be accepted into the Air Force. And I 
wanted to go on a pilot training. I said, great.

02:34.636 --> 02:35.297
When do I go? They said, well, we can't take you. 
You're only 17. We can't take you till you're 18.

02:42.324 --> 02:45.688
Well, I was just quite discouraged by it. So I was 
walking down the hall. As I recall, it was on the

02:47.230 --> 02:50.033
third floor of the federal building. As I was going 
down the hall, I ran into this cat standing next to

02:50.384 --> 03:06.145
an open doorway in a pair of dress blue uniforms 
with all the gold stripes up and down the arm,

02:50.384 --> 03:06.145
Marine Corps recruiting officer. He said, what's 
the matter son, wouldn't they take you down there?

03:08.748 --> 03:14.856
I said, oh no, they'll take me, but I have to wait 
until I'm 18 before I can go in. He said, well, come

03:15.275 --> 03:17.598
in here and talk to me. And I said, oh, no, I'm not 
interested in that. I want to fly. He said, haven't

03:21.463 --> 03:23.746
you ever heard of the Marine Air Force? I said, 
well, really, not much. He said, we've got the

03:27.972 --> 03:31.737
greatest air corps in the world. I said, well, it 
doesn't make any difference to me whether it's the

03:31.757 --> 03:36.864
Army Air Corps or the Marine Air Corps. I just 
wanted to fly. He said, tell you what to do. You come

03:39.708 --> 03:42.632
in here, and we'll fill out these recruiting 
papers. We get through with this. I'm going to

03:44.618 --> 03:50.369
write down on the bottom of it that it says, you know 
everybody has to go through boot camp at the Marine

03:44.618 --> 03:50.369
Corps. I said, oh yeah, I don't mind that. He said, 
well, as soon as you get out of boot camp, I'm going

03:51.832 --> 03:57.402
to write on here that they're sending you to 
college training school. Fine. Sign it up. I was

04:00.148 --> 04:04.536
almost through boot camp before I found out they 
didn't even have a a pilot training program. They

04:07.766 --> 04:09.389
got all their pilots out of the Navy. Which was 
probably the best thing that ever happened to me

04:11.171 --> 04:16.418
because I found out I got air sick and all that sort 
of thing. So most things that have happened to me in

04:16.478 --> 04:24.449
life that were discouraging at the time turned out 
to be a whole lot better than they looked like they

04:16.478 --> 04:24.449
were going to be. I spent some two and a half years in 
the South Pacific and the last nine months I spent

04:24.469 --> 04:32.160
in China. At the end of the war, we were on an LST 
going back from Okinawa to Guam to refit to go into

04:33.001 --> 04:41.813
Japan. That was the plan at the moment. On the way 
back to Guam, they dropped the bomb. When we landed

04:48.562 --> 04:53.708
in Guam, they said, okay, we're going to refit now. 
Rather than going to attack Japan, we're going to

04:53.769 --> 05:00.898
repatriate the Japanese Army out of North China. 
that had been there since 1937. Hold on just a

05:02.807 --> 05:04.850
second. How did you and your buddies hear the news 
of the bomb, and what was your reaction to it? We

05:11.517 --> 05:30.717
were on an LST, which is not the easiest thing to be 
on in the South Pacific, particularly since about

05:11.517 --> 05:30.717
that time we were not too far off the island of Truk, 
which is one of their big air bases, and a typhoon

05:11.517 --> 05:30.717
came up and started blowing us toward Truk. So the 
LST has a flat tank deck on the bottom, which we all

05:31.507 --> 05:41.300
were on cots and sleeping on it. The seas were so 
rough that it would buckle those plates. And a lot

05:45.727 --> 05:50.693
of the cots, when they went up, came down, break the 
legs off of them, so we slept on the floor. It was a

05:51.174 --> 05:52.596
very rough passage. We heard about it. At first, we 
didn't believe it, because we, well, these sorts

05:53.577 --> 06:00.687
of things come across, and they're really not so. 
But then we got confirmation, and everybody was

06:01.409 --> 06:20.822
extremely relieved and thought whatever it took, 
that was the greatest thing that could have

06:01.409 --> 06:20.822
happened because we were really not looking 
forward to having to go into the Japanese

06:01.409 --> 06:20.822
mainland, which we understood. Now, I was a 
private, so I did not know the grand strategy of the

06:20.862 --> 06:26.472
war effort. but even at that level we knew that it 
was going to be a very, very tough landing if we did

06:27.177 --> 06:35.346
go into Japan. So it, as I say, it was a great relief. 
Everybody was extremely happy about it. We

06:44.857 --> 06:55.429
couldn't wait to get to Guam and get a cold beverage 
there if we could and then get everything refitted

06:44.857 --> 06:55.429
and head out to China. So you're on Guam when you 
hear the war is over? No, we were still on the way to

06:57.915 --> 07:00.478
Guam. They signed the, on the USS Missouri, they 
signed the, I said decapulation, the treaty that

07:01.339 --> 07:15.176
ended the war. But of course, everyone really 
thought that when they dropped the bomb that the

07:16.257 --> 07:23.205
war would be over in a matter of days, which it 
really was. I've forgotten, it was August the You

07:25.582 --> 07:29.106
probably know the dates, but I don't remember 
exactly what it was. But we refitted in Guam,

07:30.608 --> 07:40.640
loaded up, and said this was the first early part of 
August. So we moved real quickly and landed in,

07:40.740 --> 07:54.036
moved into Tencent, China, and landed there on the 
Ohio River on September the 1st of 19... That would

07:54.910 --> 08:00.576
have been 1944 or 45.

