11:53.455 --> 12:07.718
course, didn't really need a suit down here, but 
Tacky pants and the shirts and shaving gear, and

12:08.069 --> 12:12.313
that was about it. I mean, we didn't fill up a whole 
sea bag full of it. Didn't have much. No radio,

12:17.137 --> 12:22.522
no... What kind of razor? Safety razor? Yeah, a 
safety razor. One of those straight-edge safety

12:26.146 --> 12:28.468
razors. I never did get the hang of running one of 
those deadly ones. What was your impression of the

12:33.573 --> 12:36.135
campus when you first saw it? It was sort of quite 
impressive, really, because we had not seen any

12:36.503 --> 12:44.691
campus like this, so we didn't really know what to 
expect. We were sort of quite confused as to where

12:46.173 --> 12:53.079
to go and what the next step was going to be. Of 
course, we overwhelmed, as a group of returning

12:53.100 --> 12:59.146
veterans, we overwhelmed A&M. We were in the 
biggest class they'd ever had here at that time. in

13:05.360 --> 13:10.008
the class of 1950, and of course they had no place 
for us to sleep. We didn't know that at the time, and

13:10.448 --> 13:31.924
by the time we'd finally gotten through 
registration and asked, all right, now where do

13:10.448 --> 13:31.924
we, you know, what dorm do we go to and all this sort 
of thing, he said, well, there'll be a truck come by

13:10.448 --> 13:31.924
here in a little bit that'll pick you up and take you 
out to the old Brown Air Force Base, and your

13:10.448 --> 13:31.924
quarters will be out there. So we waited, and the 
truck came by, a big flatbed truck. We threw our sea

13:36.540 --> 13:43.670
bags on there, and we got off 100 miles out in the 
sticks away from everywhere. And here was the old

13:44.451 --> 13:53.804
Bryan Air Force Base that still had their tar paper 
shacks up, and we were assigned to one of those tar

13:44.451 --> 13:53.804
paper shacks. Was that at all similar to a boot 
camp? We said, we have already been through

13:57.669 --> 14:02.876
this. So let's just forget about this and go home. 
Well, it was about dark by that time. It had taken

14:07.824 --> 14:09.807
all day to get all this done. And we said, well, 
we'll at least spend the night. And we did. And of

14:14.533 --> 14:18.879
course, I'm sure A&M has affected a whole lot of 
people that same way. After you spend a little time

14:18.980 --> 14:23.966
here, your whole attitude changes about it. And 
next morning, things were all right. And about as

14:27.752 --> 14:31.797
you look back on that group of freshmen, about how 
many of them were veterans, or what percentage?

14:39.291 --> 14:49.723
TASCAL, I don't remember what percentage, but of 
